  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Therefore thus saith the Lord God,.... Since these are their thoughts, and this the fruit of their doings: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "behold, my anger and my fury shall be poured out upon this place; like fire, to consume and destroy it; meaning Jerusalem, which was burned with fire; as an emblem of God's wrath, and an instance of his vengeance upon it, for sins; which came down in great abundance, like a storm or tempest: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "upon man and upon beast; upon beasts for the sake of man, they being his property, and for his use; otherwise they are innocent, and do not deserve the wrath of God, nor are they sensible of it: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and upon the trees of the field, and upon the fruit of your ground; which should be blighted by nipping winds, or cut down and trampled upon by the Chaldean army: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and it shall burn, and shall not be quenched; that is, the wrath of God shall burn like fire, and shall not cease until it has executed the whole will of God in the punishment of his people. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "and it shall burn, and shall not be quenched; that is, the wrath of God shall burn like fire, and shall not cease until it has executed the whole will of God in the punishment of his people. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Geneva Study Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cverse2",
        "text": "Therefore thus saith the Lord GOD; Behold, mine anger and my fury shall be poured out upon this place, upon man, and upon beast, and upon the trees of the field, and upon the fruit of the ground; and it shall burn, and shall not be quenched.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 20.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Upon man, and upon beast.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " That all creation shares in the curse of man is repeatedly affirmed in the Old Testament as well as the New. Inferentially, this doctrine appears from the narrative of the Fall, and still more clearly from Isaiah's description of Paradise regained (11.). Hosea speaks of sufferings of the animals arising out of the guilt of Israel (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 4:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and a consciousness of the \"solidarity\" of all living creatures is ascribed to a Ninevite king in the Book of Jonah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jonah 3:7, 8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). In general, the origin of this community of suffering is left mysterious, but in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 6:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it is expressly stated as the cause of the Deluge, that \"all flesh [",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "e",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". both man and beast.] had corrupted its way upon the earth;\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "e",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". apparently, that contact with man had led to a corruption of the original innocence of the lower animals. It is a common experience that intercourse between Christianized (not to say civilized) man and the domestic animals produces a sometimes pathetic change in the psychic phenomena of the latter. Is the reverse process utterly inconceivable? Jeremiah 7:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "But instead of vexing Him (Jahveh) they rather vex themselves, inasmuch as God causes the consequences of their idolatry to fall on their own head. אתם is used reflexively: se ipsos; cf. Ew. 314, c; Gesen. 124, 1, b. For the cause of the shame of their face, i.e., to prepare for themselves the shame of their face, to cover their face with shame; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 3:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". - For (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 7:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") because of this idolatrous work, the wrath of the Lord will pour itself over the land in the consuming fire of war (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 4:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 5:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nahum 1:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.), so as to cut off men and beasts, trees and fruit. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]